div.h3: Syscall Timing: The Observer Effect Breakdown

p.em: Tracing the path from hardware instruction to formatted output

div.p: Conclusion: ptrace-based timing measures the Observer Overhead, not raw kernel speed.
Layer: Hardware/Application State: Tracee: RUNNING Activity: CPU executes syscall opcode. Cost: 100 - 50,000 cycles.
Layer: Kernel Context Switch State: Tracee: STOPPED (ENTRY), Tracer: ACTIVE Activity: waitpid() returns in Tracer. Cost: ~2000 cycles.
Layer: Tracer Userspace State: Timestamp t1 = CAPTURED Activity: VDSO call to read CLOCK_MONOTONIC. Cost: ~30 cycles.
Layer: Kernel IPC State: Tracer: READING REGISTERS Activity: Copies orig_rax, rdi, rsi into ProcessState. Cost: ~500 cycles.
Layer: I/O Subsystem State: Output: BUFFERED/WRITTEN Activity: String formatting + write to file/stderr. Cost: 500 - 5,000 cycles.
Layer: Kernel IPC State: Tracee: READY TO RUN Activity: Tells kernel to resume tracee until exit boundary. Cost: ~300 cycles.
Layer: Kernel Internals State: Tracee: KERNEL MODE Activity: sys_write, sys_open, etc. executes. Cost: Actual Syscall Latency.
Layer: Kernel Context Switch State: Tracee: STOPPED (EXIT), Tracer: ACTIVE Activity: waitpid() returns result in rax. Cost: ~2000 cycles.
Layer: Kernel IPC State: Tracer: READING RESULT Activity: Copies return value from rax. Cost: ~500 cycles.
Layer: Tracer Userspace State: Timestamp t2 = CAPTURED Activity: VDSO call to read CLOCK_MONOTONIC. Cost: ~30 cycles.
